A [canoe](/Canoe) is a remarkably lightweight and slender [watercraft](/Watercraft), typically tapering to a point at both its bow and stern, and remaining open at the top. Its propulsion relies on one or more individuals who are either seated or kneeling, facing the intended direction of travel, and wielding paddles.

Within the realm of [British English](/British_English), the term "canoe" can also encompass what is commonly known as a [kayak](/Kayak). In such contexts, canoes are then specifically referred to as "Canadian" or "open canoes" to differentiate them from kayaks. However, for the purposes of official competitions, the distinction made in American English between a kayak and a canoe is almost universally adopted. This is evident in events like the Olympics, where under the overarching titles of [Canoe Slalom](/Canoe_slalom) and [Canoe Sprint](/Canoe_Sprint), there are distinct categories for both canoes and kayaks.

## Culture

The canoe's genesis can be traced to diverse cultures across the globe, with some designs even incorporating [sails](/Sail) or [outriggers](/Outrigger). For centuries, up until the mid-19th century, the canoe served as a crucial mode of transportation for exploration and trade. Even today, in certain regions, it retains its significance as a primary means of transport, occasionally augmented by the addition of an [outboard motor](/Outboard_motor).

In areas where the canoe has played a pivotal role in history, such as the [Northern United States](/Northern_United_States), [Canada](/Canada), and [New Zealand](/New_Zealand), it continues to hold a prominent place in [popular culture](/Popular_culture). A prime example is the [birch bark](/Birch_bark) canoe, an indispensable tool for the [First Nations of Quebec, Canada, and North America](/First_Nations_in_Canada), whose reliance on birch trees for their livelihood was matched by the mobility this vessel afforded their hunting practices.

Currently, canoes are extensively utilized in competitive sports. In fact, canoeing has been a fixture in the [Olympic Games](/Olympic_Games) since the [1936 Summer Olympics](/1936_Summer_Olympics). Beyond competition, they are widely embraced for leisure activities such as [racing](/Canoe_racing), [whitewater](/Whitewater_canoeing) excursions, touring expeditions, [camping](/Canoe_camping) adventures, [freestyle](/Canoe_freestyle) maneuvers, and general [recreation](/Recreation).

The specific intended use of a canoe fundamentally dictates its [hull](/Hull_(watercraft)) shape, its overall [length](/Length_overall), and the materials used in its construction. While historically canoes were fashioned from dugouts or constructed from bark stretched over a wooden frame, materials evolved to include canvas over a wood frame, and subsequently, aluminum. The vast majority of contemporary canoes are now manufactured from molded plastic or advanced [composites](/Composite_material) like [fiberglass](/Fiberglass), often incorporating materials such as [Kevlar](/Kevlar) or [graphite](/Graphite).

## History

The English word "canoe" is believed to have originated from the Spanish term 'canoa,' which appeared in [Columbus' travelogues](/Columbus%27s_letter_on_the_first_voyage) in 1493, referring to the dugout canoes of the Caribbean. It is plausible that 'canoa' itself derives from the Taino word `kanawa`, used by the indigenous inhabitants of the Caribbean for this type of vessel. After its adoption into Spanish, the term "canoa" subsequently found its way into the French language. While the French adopted a form similar to the Spanish, such as "canoë" or "canot," there is also evidence suggesting a potential influence from other indigenous languages encountered by French explorers in North America. For instance, the French word "casnouey" was adopted from the Saint-Lawrence Iroquoians language in the 1535 Jacques Cartier Relations, later translated into English in 1600 by the geographer [Richard Hakluyt](/Richard_Hakluyt).

### Dugouts

The practice of crafting dugout canoes, carved from a single piece of wood—either a whole [trunk](/Trunk_(botany)) or a substantial slab from exceptionally large trees—has a long and widespread history. Dugout canoes date back to antiquity. The [Dufuna canoe](/Dufuna_canoe), unearthed in Nigeria, has been carbon-dated to between 8500 and 8000 BC. Similarly, the [Pesse canoe](/Pesse_canoe), discovered in the Netherlands, is estimated to be from 8200–7600 BC. Archaeological excavations in [Denmark](/Denmark) have revealed the use of dugouts and paddles during the [Ertebølle](/Erteb%C3%B8lle_culture) period, which spanned approximately 5300 to 3950 BC.

Canoes played an indispensable role in the colonization of the [pre-Columbian](/Pre-Columbian_era) [Caribbean](/Caribbean), as they represented the sole means of traversing from mainland South America to the islands. Around 3500 BC, ancient [Amerindian](/Indigenous_peoples_of_the_Americas) groups embarked on colonizing the initial Caribbean islands, utilizing single-hulled canoes for their journeys. To date, only a limited number of pre-Columbian Caribbean canoes have been recovered. The construction of these canoes likely involved a variety of tree species, potentially including those from the [mahogany](/Mahogany) family (Meliaceae), such as the [Cuban mahogany](/Swietenia_mahagoni) (*Swietenia mahagoni*), known for growing to heights of 30 to 35 meters (100 to 110 ft). Other candidates include red cedar ([Cedrela odorata](/Cedrela_odorata)), which can reach up to 60 meters (200 ft), and species from the [ceiba](/Ceiba) genus (Malvacae), such as [Ceiba pentandra](/Ceiba_pentandra), capable of attaining heights of 60 to 70 meters (200 to 230 ft). It is reasonable to assume these canoes were built in various sizes, from small fishing vessels accommodating one or a few individuals to larger craft capable of transporting several dozen people, facilitating their migration across the Caribbean. Historical accounts from [chroniclers](/Chronicle) even mention witnessing a canoe "containing 40 to 50 [Caribs](/Island_Caribs)... when it came out to trade with a visiting English ship."

There remains considerable debate regarding the use of sails in Caribbean canoes. Some archaeologists express skepticism about the feasibility of oceanic transportation without sails, given the potential for winds and currents to push canoes off course. However, no direct evidence of sails or Caribbean canoes specifically designed to accommodate them has been found. Furthermore, historical records do not mention Caribbean canoes equipped with sails. One hypothesis suggests that canoes with sails might have been employed in the Caribbean initially but were later abandoned before European contact. This, however, seems improbable, as long-distance trade persisted in the region even after the prehistoric colonization of the islands. Therefore, it is more likely that early Caribbean colonists relied on canoes propelled solely by human power.

Indigenous groups along the [Pacific Northwest](/Pacific_Northwest) coast of North America expertly crafted dugout canoes in a variety of styles tailored to different purposes, utilizing either western red cedar ([Thuja plicata](/Thuja_plicata)) or yellow cedar ([Chamaecyparis nootkatensis](/Chamaecyparis_nootkatensis)), depending on local availability. Distinct designs were necessary for ocean-going vessels compared to river craft, and for specialized hunting practices such as [whale-hunting](/Whaling) or [seal-hunting](/Seal_hunting), as well as for [salmon](/Salmon) fishing. The [Quinault](/Quinault_people) of [Washington State](/Washington_(state)) constructed "shovel-nose" canoes, characterized by double bows, which were ideal for river travel and could navigate over [logjams](/Log_jam) without the need for [portaging](/Portaging). The [Kootenai](/Kutenai_people) of the Canadian province of British Columbia fashioned "sturgeon-nosed canoes" from pine bark, designed for enhanced stability on the often windy conditions of [Kootenay Lake](/Kootenay_Lake).

In recent decades, First Nations communities in British Columbia and [Washington State](/Washington_(state)) have actively engaged in reviving the tradition of ocean-going canoes. The [Heiltsuk](/Heiltsuk) and [Haida](/Haida_people) were among the early pioneers in this revitalization movement, beginning in the 1980s. Notable early events included the "Paddle to Expo 86" in Vancouver, organized by the Heiltsuk, and the 1989 "Paddle to [Seattle](/Seattle)," which brought together multiple Native American tribes to commemorate Washington State's centennial. The movement continued to grow, culminating in the establishment of [Tribal Journeys](/Tribal_Canoe_Journeys) in 1993, an initiative that began with a large gathering of canoes paddling to [Bella Bella](/Bella_Bella,_British_Columbia) for its inaugural canoe festival, Qatuwas. These journeys, held annually in most years, have become a significant cultural event.

[Aboriginal Australian](/Aboriginal_Australian) peoples traditionally constructed canoes by hollowing out [tree trunks](/Trunk_(botany)), and also by utilizing tree bark. The indigenous populations of the [Amazon](/Amazon_Basin) commonly employed trees from the [Hymenaea](/Hymenaea) genus (Fabaceae) for this purpose.

### Bark canoes

#### Australia

Certain [Aboriginal Australian](/Aboriginal_Australian) groups crafted bark canoes. These were typically made from the bark of specific trees, most notably [red gum](/Eucalyptus_camaldulensis) or [box gum](/Box_gum), and were constructed during the summer months. The process involved cutting the bark to the desired size and shape, then using a digging stick to sever it from the underlying hardwood. The detached bark was subsequently pried loose using smaller sticks and held in shape by branches or handwoven ropes. Once separated from the tree, the bark was carefully lowered to the ground. Small fires were then lit inside the bark to facilitate drying and cause it to curl upwards. The ends were then pulled together and stitched with hemp, and the seams were sealed with mud. The finished canoe was allowed to cure, with periodic applications of [grease](/Animal_fat) and [ochre](/Ochre). The trees from which the bark was harvested were later referred to as [canoe trees](/Canoe_tree) by Europeans.

Due to the inherent porosity of bark, these canoes had a limited lifespan, typically lasting only about two years. They were primarily used for fishing or for crossing rivers and lakes, thereby avoiding longer, more arduous overland journeys. Propulsion was usually achieved by punting with a long stick. Another type of bark canoe involved pleating and tying the bark of messmate stringybark ([Eucalyptus obliqua](/Eucalyptus_obliqua)) at each end, reinforced with a framework of cross-ties and ribs. This style was known as a pleated or tied bark canoe. Bark strips could also be sewn together to construct larger canoes, referred to as sewn bark canoes.

#### Americas

Many [indigenous peoples of the Americas](/Indigenous_peoples_of_the_Americas) were skilled builders of bark canoes. These vessels were most commonly constructed using the bark of the [paper birch](/Betula_papyrifera), harvested in early spring by carefully stripping the bark in a single piece using wooden wedges. The bow ([stem](/Bow_(watercraft))) and stern ([stern](/Stern)) were then sewn together and rendered watertight with the [pitch](/Pitch_(resin)) derived from [balsam fir](/Abies_balsamea). The internal ribs, known as *verons* in [Canadian French](/Canadian_French), were fashioned from [white cedar](/Thuja_occidentalis). The hull, ribs, and thwarts were secured using [watap](/Watap), a binding typically made from the [roots](/Root) of various conifer species, such as [white spruce](/Picea_glauca), [black spruce](/Picea_mariana), or [cedar](/Thuja_occidentalis). The seams were then caulked with [pitch](/Pitch_(resin)).

With an average length of 4.3 meters (14 ft) and a weight of approximately 23 kg (50 lb), these canoes were remarkably light, allowing for easy [portaging](/Portage), yet possessed sufficient capacity to transport considerable cargo, even in shallow waters. While susceptible to damage from rocks, they were also relatively easy to repair. Their exceptional performance characteristics were quickly recognized by early European [settler colonials](/European_colonization_of_the_Americas), and canoes played a pivotal role in the [exploration of North America](/Exploration_of_North_America). [Samuel de Champlain](/Samuel_de_Champlain), for instance, journeyed by canoe as far as [Georgian Bay](/Georgian_Bay) in 1615.

In 1603, a canoe was presented at [Sir Robert Cecil](/Sir_Robert_Cecil)'s [house](/Cecil_House) in London, and was subsequently rowed on the [River Thames](/River_Thames) by [Virginian Indians](/Powhatan) from [Tsenacommacah](/Tsenacommacah). By 1643, [David Pietersz. de Vries](/David_Pietersz._de_Vries) documented a [Mohawk](/Mohawk_people) canoe in Dutch possession at [Rensselaerswyck](/Manor_of_Rensselaerswyck) that was reportedly capable of transporting 225 [bushels](/Bushel) of maize. [René de Bréhant de Galinée](/Ren%C3%A9_de_Br%C3%A9hant_de_Galin%C3%A9e), a French [missionary](/Missionary) who explored the [Great Lakes](/Great_Lakes) in 1669, remarked on the practicality of these canoes in navigating waters filled with cataracts and rapids, where other boats could not pass. He noted that when encountering such obstacles, the canoe and its contents would be carried overland until navigable waters were reached, allowing for re-embarkation. The American painter, author, and traveler [George Catlin](/George_Catlin) lauded the bark canoe as "the most beautiful and light model of all the water crafts that ever were invented."

The first European explorer to successfully cross the North American continent, [Alexander Mackenzie](/Alexander_Mackenzie_(explorer)), relied heavily on canoes throughout his expeditions, as did other notable figures such as [David Thompson](/David_Thompson_(explorer)) and the members of the [Lewis and Clark Expedition](/Lewis_and_Clark_Expedition).

Within the context of the [North American fur trade](/North_American_fur_trade), the [Hudson's Bay Company](/Hudson%27s_Bay_Company)'s [voyageurs](/Voyageurs) utilized three primary types of canoe:

*   The **rabaska** (French: *canot du maître*, meaning "master canoe," though some sources attribute the name to an artisan named Louise Le Maître from the Province of Quebec) – also known as the "Montreal canoe" – was specifically designed for extensive journeys from the [St. Lawrence River](/St._Lawrence_River) to the western reaches of [Lake Superior](/Lake_Superior). These formidable vessels measured approximately 11 meters (35 ft) in length, with a beam ranging from 1.2 to 1.8 meters (4 to 6 ft), and a height of about 76 cm (30 in). They possessed the capacity to carry 60 packs, each weighing 40 kg (90 lb), along with 900 kg (2,000 lb) of provisions. Crewed by eight to ten paddlers or rowers, they could achieve speeds of three knots on calm waters. Four to six individuals could manage to [portage](/Portage) them, carried upside down. [Henry Schoolcraft](/Henry_Schoolcraft) described it as "altogether one of the most eligible modes of conveyance that can be employed upon the lakes." [Archibald McDonald](/Archibald_McDonald) of the Hudson's Bay Company attested to their seaworthiness, stating, "I never heard of such a canoe being wrecked, or upset, or swamped ... they swam like ducks."

*   The **canot du nord** (French: "canoe of the north") was a craft meticulously built and adapted for rapid transit, serving as the backbone of the fur trade transportation system. Approximately half the size of the rabaska, it could carry around 35 packs, each weighing 40 kg (90 lb), and was manned by a crew of four to eight individuals. These canoes were light enough to be carried by just two men and were typically portaged in an upright position.

*   The **express canoe** (French: *"canot léger"*, meaning "light canoe*) measured about 4.6 meters (15 ft) in length and was primarily used for transporting personnel, dispatches, and important news.

The birchbark canoe was integral to a vast supply route stretching 6,500 kilometers (4,000 mi) from [Montreal](/Montreal) to the Pacific Ocean and the [Mackenzie River](/Mackenzie_River). Its use persisted until the close of the 19th century. By that time, the traditional manufacturing techniques for birchbark canoes had largely fallen into disuse and were nearly lost to history, until their methods were painstakingly revived by [Tappan Adney](/Tappan_Adney).

The [indigenous peoples](/Indigenous_peoples_of_the_Americas) of eastern Canada and the northeastern United States mastered the construction of canoes using the bark of the [paper birch](/Betula_papyrifera). This process involved harvesting the bark in early spring, carefully stripping it from the tree in a single piece using wooden wedges. The bow and stern were then sewn together and sealed for watertightness with the resinous [pitch](/Pitch_(resin)) of the [balsam fir](/Abies_balsamea). The internal ribs of the canoe, known as *verons* in [Canadian French](/Canadian_French), were crafted from [white cedar](/Thuja_occidentalis). The hull, ribs, and thwarts were secured using [watap](/Watap), a strong binding typically made from the fibrous [roots](/Root) of various conifer species, such as the [white spruce](/Picea_glauca), [black spruce](/Picea_mariana), or [cedar](/Thuja_occidentalis). Finally, the seams were caulked with [pitch](/Pitch_(resin)).

### Skin canoes

Skin canoes are characterized by their construction method, which involves stretching animal skins over a supporting framework. Prominent examples of this type include the [kayak](/Kayak) and the [umiak](/Umiak).

### Modern canoes

In 19th-century North America, the traditional birch-on-frame construction technique evolved into the production of wood-and-canvas canoes. This method involved fastening an external, waterproofed [canvas](/Canvas) shell to a framework of planks and ribs. Renowned boat builders such as [Old Town Canoe](/Old_Town_Canoe), [E. M. White Canoe](/E.M._White_Canoe_Company), [Peterborough Canoe Company](/Peterborough_Canoe_Company), and the [Chestnut Canoe Company](/Chestnut_Canoe_Company) in [New Brunswick](/New_Brunswick) were pioneers in this craft. Although similar to bark canoes in their use of [ribs](/Frame_(nautical)) and a waterproof covering, the construction process differed significantly, as these canoes were built over a solid mold. Once removed from the mold, decks, [thwarts](/Thwart), and [seats](/Seat) were installed, and canvas was stretched tautly over the hull. This canvas was then treated with a combination of [varnishes](/Varnish) and [paints](/Paint) to enhance its durability and ensure [watertightness](/Waterproofing).

While canoes were once primarily a utilitarian means of transport, the advent of industrialization saw them gain popularity as [recreational](/Recreation) and sporting watercraft. [John MacGregor](/John_MacGregor_(sportsman)), through his published works, played a significant role in popularizing canoeing. He was instrumental in founding the [Royal Canoe Club](/Royal_Canoe_Club) in London in 1866 and the [American Canoe Association](/American_Canoe_Association) in 1880. The [Canadian Canoe Association](/Canadian_Canoe_Association) was established in 1900, followed by the [British Canoe Union](/British_Canoe_Union) in 1936. In Sweden, naval officer [Carl Smith](/Carl_Smith_(canoeing)) was a fervent advocate for canoeing and also a designer of innovative, sometimes experimental, canoes towards the end of the 19th century.

[Sprint canoe](/Sprint_canoe) was featured as a [demonstration sport](/Demonstration_sport) at the [1924 Paris Olympics](/1924_Paris_Olympics) and officially became an Olympic discipline at the [1936 Berlin Olympics](/Canoeing_at_the_1936_Summer_Olympics). The formation of the [International Canoe Federation](/International_Canoe_Federation) in 1946 established it as the global governing body for all national canoeing organizations worldwide.

#### Hull design

The design of a canoe's [hull](/Hull_(watercraft)) must meticulously balance various, often competing, requirements such as speed, carrying capacity, maneuverability, and stability. The theoretical [hull speed](/Hull_speed) of a canoe can be determined through the application of principles governing [ship resistance and propulsion](/Ship_resistance_and_propulsion).

Canoes invariably incorporate a center thwart, a structural element designed to maintain the rigidity of the boat. This center thwart is frequently shaped to serve a dual purpose, acting as a portage [yoke](/Shoulder_pole) for easier carrying. Many canoes are also equipped with a stern thwart, typically positioned midway between the center thwart and the stern seat. Some designs include a bow thwart, usually situated just behind the bow seat.

*   **Length:** While manufacturers often state the [overall length of the boat](/Length_overall), the critical measurement for performance is the [length](/Waterline_length) of the [waterline](/Waterline). More precisely, it's the ratio of the waterline length to the canoe's [displacement](/Displacement_(ship)) – the volume of water it displaces, which is equivalent to the total weight of the canoe and its contents when floating. The fundamental principle is that paddling a canoe requires energy to displace water. Canoes are classified as [displacement hulls](/Displacement_hull): the greater the waterline length relative to its displacement, the faster it can be paddled. For general touring purposes, a length of 5.2 meters (17 ft) is a popular choice, offering a favorable balance between carrying capacity and cruising speed. A canoe that is excessively long will simply necessitate more effort to paddle at cruising speed.

*   **Width (beam):** A wider hull provides enhanced stability but comes at the cost of reduced speed. A canoe functions like a wedge cutting through water, and a shorter boat requires a narrower beam to minimize the angle of this wedge. Canoe manufacturers typically provide three beam measurements: the gunwale (measured at the top edge of the hull), the waterline (measured at the point where the water surface meets the hull when the canoe is empty), and the widest point of the hull. Another variation of the waterline beam measurement is the "4-inch waterline," which takes displacement into account. This measurement is taken at the waterline level when the canoe is carrying its maximum load. Some canoe races utilize the 4-inch waterline beam measurement as a standard in their regulations. In racing contexts, this measurement is taken at the widest point, 4 inches (10 cm) from the bottom of the canoe.

*   **Freeboard:** A boat with higher sides offers better protection against rough water, keeping the occupants drier. The drawbacks of high sides include increased weight and greater [windage](/Windage), which can negatively impact speed and steering control in crosswinds.

*   **Stability and immersed bottom shape:** The hull can be designed to optimize either initial stability (the feeling of steadiness when the boat is level on the water) or final stability (resistance to rolling and capsizing). A flatter-bottomed hull generally exhibits higher initial stability. Conversely, a hull with a rounder or V-shaped cross-section offers greater final stability. The fastest flat-water canoes, excluding racing models, feature sharp V-bottoms designed to cut through water efficiently. However, these are more challenging to turn and possess a deeper [draft](/Draft_(hull)), making them less suitable for shallow waters. Flat-bottomed canoes are favored by recreational paddlers due to their shallow draft, ample cargo space, and improved turning ability. The reason for their lower final stability lies in the sharper angle the hull must make between its bottom and sides, compared to a more rounded hull.

*   **Keel:** An external keel enhances a canoe's ability to track (maintain a straight course) and can provide stiffness to a flexible hull. However, it can also snag on rocks and reduce stability in [rapids](/Rapids).

*   **Profile:** This refers to the shape of the canoe's sides. Sides that [flare](/Flare_(ship)) outwards above the waterline effectively deflect water but necessitate the paddler reaching further over the side. Conversely, sides that curve inwards, resulting in the gunwale width being less than the maximum hull width, are described as having [tumblehome](/Tumblehome). Tumblehome contributes to improved final stability.

*   **Rocker:** When viewed from the side, rocker refers to the degree of curvature in the hull relative to the water, akin to the arc of a banana. A canoe with a minimal rocker has its entire hull length in contact with the water, promoting good tracking and speed. As the rocker increases, so does the ease of turning, but this comes at the expense of tracking ability. Some Native American birch-bark canoes were characterized by extreme rocker.

*   **Hull symmetry:** When viewed from above, a symmetrical hull has its widest point at the center, with both the bow and stern being identical. An asymmetrical hull typically features its widest section aft of the centerline, resulting in a longer bow and consequently improved speed.

#### Modern materials and construction

*   **Plastic:**
    [Folding](/Folding_boat) canoes often feature a [PVC](/PVC) skin stretched over an aluminum frame.
    [Inflatable](/Inflatable_boat) canoes are constructed without rigid frame components and can be deflated, folded, and stored in bags or boxes. More robust versions consist of an abrasion-resistant nylon or [rubber](/Natural_rubber) outer shell encasing separate PVC air chambers for the side tubes and floor.
    [Royalex](/Royalex), a [composite material](/Composite_material) consisting of an outer vinyl and hard [acrylonitrile butadiene styrene](/Acrylonitrile_butadiene_styrene) (ABS) plastic layer, with an inner ABS foam layer bonded through heat treatment, was a popular plastic alternative for canoes until 2014, when its sole manufacturer discontinued the raw composite material. Canoes made from Royalex were lighter, more resistant to [UV](/Ultraviolet) degradation, and more rigid than non-composite plastics like [polyethylene](/Polyethylene), possessing greater structural memory. However, Royalex canoes were more expensive than those made from aluminum or from [traditionally molded](/Molding_(process)) or [roto-molded](/Rotational_molding) [polyethylene](/Polyethylene) hulls. Royalex was heavier and less suitable for high-performance paddling compared to fiber-reinforced composites such as [fiberglass](/Fiberglass), [Kevlar](/Kevlar), or [graphite](/Graphite).

*   **Fiber-reinforced composites:**
    Modern canoes are typically manufactured by layering fiber materials within a "female" mold. [Fiberglass](/Fiberglass) is the most prevalent material used in canoe production. It is relatively inexpensive, can be molded into virtually any shape, and is easy to repair. [Kevlar](/Kevlar) is a favored choice among paddlers seeking a lightweight, durable boat that can withstand the rigors of whitewater. While both fiberglass and Kevlar are strong, they lack inherent rigidity. [Carbon fiber](/Carbon_fiber) is employed in the construction of racing canoes to achieve exceptional lightness and rigidity, often combined with Kevlar for enhanced durability. Boat construction involves draping the fabric within a mold and then impregnating it with a liquid [resin](/Resin). A vacuum process may optionally be used to remove excess resin, thereby reducing the overall weight.
    A [gel coat](/Gelcoat) applied to the exterior provides a smoother finish.
    In the [stitch-and-glue](/Stitch_and_glue) method, [plywood](/Plywood) panels are stitched together to form the hull shape, and the seams are subsequently reinforced with fiber-reinforced composites and varnished.
    A cedar strip canoe can be considered a composite canoe with a cedar core. Typically, fiberglass is used to reinforce the structure, and its transparency allows the attractive cedar grain to be visible.

*   **Aluminum:**
    Prior to the development of fiberglass, aluminum was the standard material for [whitewater canoeing](/Whitewater_canoeing) due to its favorable strength-to-weight ratio and durability. Although once more popular, aluminum is increasingly being supplanted by lighter, modern materials. Aluminum is recognized for its toughness, durability, and resistance to abrasion, making it well-suited for being dragged over rough surfaces. The hull is not susceptible to degradation from prolonged exposure to sunlight, and temperature extremes do not adversely affect the material. However, aluminum can dent, is difficult to repair, produces noise, can become lodged on underwater obstacles, and requires the installation of buoyancy chambers to aid in keeping the canoe afloat in the event of a capsize.

*   **Strip-built:**
    [Strip-built](/Strip-built) canoes are constructed using thin strips of wood, most commonly cedar, laid over a mold to shape the hull. The exterior and interior are then laminated with fiberglass and epoxy resin to ensure strength, durability, and water resistance. This process results in a ribless composite structure with fiberglass skins and a wood core. The natural wood grain remains visible in the finished canoe, often lending it an attractive aesthetic.

## Canoes in culture

In [Canada](/Canada), the canoe is deeply embedded in the nation's history and folklore, serving as a potent symbol of [Canadian identity](/Canadian_identity). From 1935 to 1986, the reverse side of the [Voyageur dollar](/Voyageur_dollar) coin featured an image of a canoe carrying a voyageur (a French-Canadian fur trader) and an Indigenous man.

The [Chasse-galerie](/Chasse-galerie) is a well-known [French-Canadian](/French-Canadian) folktale that recounts the story of voyageurs who, after a night of revelry on New Year's Eve at a remote logging camp, yearn to visit their sweethearts located some 100 [leagues](/League_(unit)) (approximately 400 km) away. Facing the challenge of returning in time for work the following morning, they strike a pact with the [devil](/Devil). Their canoe is granted the ability to fly through the air, with the strict conditions that they must not utter God's name or touch the cross of any [church steeple](/Steeple) as they traverse the sky. One rendition of this fable concludes with a dramatic twist: upon completing the perilous journey, the canoe overturns while still airborne, allowing the devil to uphold his pact by delivering the voyageurs while simultaneously claiming their souls.

In [John Steinbeck](/John_Steinbeck)'s novella [The Pearl](/The_Pearl_(novel)), set in Mexico, the protagonist's canoe is portrayed as a vital means of livelihood, passed down through generations, and symbolizes a profound connection to cultural heritage.

The [Māori](/M%C4%81ori_people), the indigenous [Polynesian people](/Polynesians) of [New Zealand](/New_Zealand), arrived in the islands through a series of voyaging canoe (known as [waka](/Waka_(canoe))) expeditions. Canoe traditions hold significant cultural importance for the Māori identity. [Whakapapa](/Whakapapa), or genealogical lineage, tracing back to the crews of founding canoes, served to establish tribal origins and define tribal territories and relationships.

## Types of canoes

Modern canoes are generally categorized based on their intended use. Many contemporary canoe designs are hybrids, incorporating elements from multiple designs to cater to a range of activities. The intended purpose of the canoe also frequently influences the choice of materials used in its construction. While most canoes are designed for solo paddling, others are intended for tandem use (two paddlers), and some are built to accommodate more than two individuals.

### Sprint

*   **Main articles:** [Sprint canoe](/Sprint_canoe) and [Canoe sprint](/Canoe_sprint)

[Sprint canoe](/Sprint_canoe) competitions, also known as flatwater racing, involve paddlers kneeling on one knee and using a single-bladed [paddle](/Paddle). Since canoes lack a [rudder](/Rudder), athletes must skillfully steer using their paddle, employing techniques such as the [J-stroke](/Canoe_paddle_strokes). Sprint canoes can be entirely open or partially decked. The minimum length of the opening on a C1 canoe is 280 cm (110 in). These boats are characterized by their long, streamlined shape and narrow [beam](/Beam_(nautical)), which contributes to their inherent instability. A C4 canoe can reach lengths of up to 9 meters (30 ft) and weigh as little as 30 kg (66 lb). The [International Canoe Federation](/International_Canoe_Federation) (ICF) classifications include C1 (solo), C2 (two paddlers), and C4 (four paddlers). Race distances at the [2012 Olympic Games](/2012_Olympic_Games) included 200 and 1000 meters.

### Slalom and wildwater

*   **Main articles:** [Canoe slalom](/Canoe_slalom) and [Wildwater canoeing](/Wildwater_canoeing)

In ICF [whitewater slalom](/Whitewater_slalom), competitors navigate a 300-meter (980 ft) course of [whitewater](/Whitewater) [rapids](/Rapids), passing through a series of up to 25 gates (pairs of hanging poles). The color of the poles indicates the required direction of passage through the gate; penalties are incurred for striking poles or missing gates. The categories include C1 (solo) and C2 (tandem). The C2 category is further divided into "two men" and "mixed" (one woman and one man). C1 boats must meet minimum weight and width requirements of 10 kg (22 lb) and 0.65 meters (2 ft 2 in) respectively, with a maximum length of 3.5 meters (11 ft). C2 boats must have a minimum weight and width of 15 kg (33 lb) and 0.75 meters (2 ft 6 in), and a maximum length of 4.1 meters (13 ft). Rudders are prohibited. Canoes in this discipline are decked and propelled by single-bladed paddles, with the competitor kneeling.

ICF [wildwater canoeing](/Wildwater_canoeing) involves athletes paddling through sections of whitewater classified as Class III to IV (according to the [International Scale of River Difficulty](/International_Scale_of_River_Difficulty)). Competitors navigate waves, holes, and rocks on a natural riverbed in races lasting either 20–30 minutes ("Classic" races) or 2–3 minutes ("Sprint" races). The categories are C1 and C2 for both women and men. C1 boats must have a minimum weight and width of 12 kg (26 lb) and 0.7 meters (2 ft 4 in), and a maximum length of 4.3 meters (14 ft). C2 boats must have a minimum weight and width of 18 kg (40 lb) and 0.8 meters (2 ft 7 in), and a maximum length of 5 meters (16 ft). Rudders are prohibited. These canoes are decked vessels, propelled by single-bladed paddles, with the paddler kneeling inside.

### Marathon

*   **Main article:** [Canoe marathon](/Canoe_marathon)

[Marathons](/Canoe_marathon) are long-distance races that may incorporate [portages](/Portage). Under ICF regulations, the minimum weight for C1 and C2 canoes is 10 kg (22 lb) and 14 kg (31 lb), respectively. Other rules can vary depending on the specific race. For instance, in the Classique Internationale de Canots de la [Mauricie](/Mauricie) race, C2 canoes have a maximum length of 5.6 meters (18 ft 6 in), a minimum width of 69 cm (27 in) measured 8 cm (3 in) from the bottom at the center of the craft, and minimum heights of 38 cm (15 in) at the bow and 25 cm (10 in) at the center and stern. The [Texas Water Safari](/Texas_Water_Safari), spanning 422 km (262 mi), includes an open class where the only rule is that the vessel must be [human-powered](/Human-powered_watercraft). While various innovative configurations have been attempted, the fastest vessel recorded to date has been a six-man canoe.

### Touring

*   **See also:** [Canoe camping](/Canoe_camping)

A "touring" or "tripping" canoe is designed for traveling on lakes and rivers, with ample space for [camping](/Camping) gear. Tripping canoes, such as the [Chestnut](/Chestnut_Canoe_Company) Prospector and its derivatives from [Old Town Canoe](/Old_Town_Canoe), are specifically built for [wilderness](/Wilderness) expeditions. They are typically constructed from heavier, more durable materials and engineered to carry substantial loads while maintaining sufficient maneuverability for navigating rivers with moderate [whitewater](/Whitewater). The term "Prospector" has become a generic descriptor for models derived from the original [Chestnut](/Chestnut_Canoe_Company) design, a popular choice for wilderness tripping. The Prospector design is characterized by a shallow arch hull and a relatively pronounced rocker, providing an optimal balance for wilderness tripping across both lakes and rivers with some [rapids](/Rapids).

Touring canoes are sometimes fitted with an extended deck, creating a "cockpit" area for the paddlers. This cockpit design offers the advantage of allowing for lower and narrower gunwales, facilitating easier reach to the water for paddling.

### Freestyle

A freestyle canoe is a specialized craft designed for [whitewater](/Whitewater) play and performing tricks. Most freestyle canoes are virtually identical to short, flat-bottomed [kayak](/Kayak) playboats, differing primarily in their internal outfitting. The paddler kneels and uses a single-bladed canoe paddle. Playboating is a discipline within whitewater canoeing where the paddler executes various technical maneuvers at a stationary location (a "playspot"), as opposed to downriver racing, where the objective is to cover the length of a river section. While whitewater canoeists often stop to engage in playboating during downriver trips, specialized canoes known as playboats are used for this discipline.

### Square-stern canoe

A square-stern canoe is an asymmetrical design featuring a squared-off [stern](/Stern) that allows for the mounting of an [outboard motor](/Outboard_motor). These canoes are primarily intended for lake travel or fishing. Given the ease with which a [rudder](/Rudder) can be affixed to the square stern, such canoes are frequently adapted for [sailing](/Sailing).

## Canoe launches

A canoe launch is a designated area for entering and exiting the water with canoes, similar in function to a [boat launch](/Boat_launch) which typically serves larger watercraft. Canoe launches are commonly situated on [river banks](/River_banks) or [beaches](/Beaches). They may be indicated on [maps](/Maps) of areas such as [parks](/Parks) or [nature reserves](/Nature_reserves).

